---
import BaseLayout from '~/layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import PageHeader from '~/components/PageHeader.astro';
import { papers } from '~/config';

const paper = papers.find((p) => p.slug === 'elliptic-functions')!;

const toc = [
  { id: 's1', label: '1. Motivation, lemniscatic arc length' },
  { id: 's2', label: '2. The torus ℂ/Λ and compactness' },
  { id: 's3', label: '3. Liouville\'s theorems' },
  { id: 's4', label: '4. The Weierstrass ℘-function' },
  { id: 's5', label: '5. The differential equation (℘\')² = 4℘³ − g₂℘ − g₃' },
  { id: 's6', label: '6. Representation: E(Λ) = ℂ(℘, ℘\')' },
  { id: 's7', label: '7. The j-invariant and the modular group' },
  { id: 's8', label: '8. The Jacobi sn / cn / dn family' },
  { id: 's9', label: '9. Application, the exact large-amplitude pendulum' },
  { id: 's10', label: '10. Application, KdV cnoidal waves' },
  { id: 's11', label: '11. Closing the loop, arc length of the lemniscate' },
];
---

<BaseLayout title={paper.title} description={paper.abstract}>
  <PageHeader eyebrow={`Research · ${paper.date} · Deep dive`} title={paper.title} />

  <section class="container-wide pb-24 grid lg:grid-cols-[minmax(0,1fr)_260px] gap-10">
    <!-- Main content -->
    <article class="min-w-0">
      <!-- Metadata -->
      <div class="card anim-in anim-stagger-1 mb-10">
        <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-4 text-sm">
          <div>
            <span class="eyebrow mb-1">Authors</span>
            <p class="text-ink-800">{paper.authors}</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="eyebrow mb-1">Venue</span>
            <p class="text-ink-800">{paper.venue}</p>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="eyebrow mb-1">Topics</span>
            <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-1.5 mt-1">
              {paper.tags.map((t) => <span class="tag-domain">{t}</span>)}
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="anim-in anim-stagger-2 space-y-6 text-ink-800 leading-relaxed">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold">Abstract</h2>
        <p>{paper.abstract}</p>

        <section id="s1" class="scroll-mt-24 pt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">1. Motivation, the lemniscatic arc length</h2>
          <p>
            The story starts with a deceptively simple curve, the lemniscate
            of Bernoulli, and the problem of computing its arc length. The
            integral doesn't close under elementary functions. This is the
            symptom that elliptic integrals exist as a genuinely new class.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="s2" class="scroll-mt-24 pt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">2. The torus ℂ/Λ and compactness</h2>
          <p>
            A doubly-periodic meromorphic function lives naturally on the
            quotient ℂ/Λ, where Λ = ℤω₁ ⊕ ℤω₂ is a rank-2 lattice. The
            quotient is compact, which makes the entire theory, Liouville's
            theorems, pole counts, the residue sum, fall out almost for free.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="s3" class="scroll-mt-24 pt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">3. Liouville's theorems</h2>
          <p>
            Four classical statements: a holomorphic elliptic function is
            constant; the sum of residues in a fundamental parallelogram is
            zero; every non-constant elliptic function has equal zero and pole
            counts; zeros and poles sum to the same class mod Λ.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="s4" class="scroll-mt-24 pt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">4. The Weierstrass ℘-function</h2>
          <p>
            Construct ℘(z; Λ) = 1/z² + Σ [1/(z-ω)² − 1/ω²] over non-zero
            lattice points ω. Show convergence, prove evenness, and establish
            that ℘ is an elliptic function of order 2.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="s5" class="scroll-mt-24 pt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">5. The differential equation</h2>
          <p>
            (℘')² = 4℘³ − g₂℘ − g₃. The invariants g₂, g₃ are lattice sums.
            This is the gateway to viewing ℘ as parameterizing an elliptic
            curve y² = 4x³ − g₂x − g₃.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="s6" class="scroll-mt-24 pt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">6. Representation: E(Λ) = ℂ(℘, ℘')</h2>
          <p>
            Every elliptic function with lattice Λ is a rational function of ℘
            and ℘'. Split into even and odd parts; the even part is a
            rational function of ℘, the odd part is ℘' times a rational
            function of ℘.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="s7" class="scroll-mt-24 pt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">7. The j-invariant and the modular group</h2>
          <p>
            j(Λ) = 1728·g₂³ / (g₂³ − 27g₃²). Classifies lattices up to complex
            multiplication and connects to SL(2,ℤ) acting on the upper
            half-plane.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="s8" class="scroll-mt-24 pt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">8. The Jacobi sn / cn / dn family</h2>
          <p>
            A more applied parameterization. sn(u, k) generalizes sine; cn and
            dn are its trigonometric cousins. The modulus k controls how far
            from elementary-trig we sit.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="s9" class="scroll-mt-24 pt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">9. Application, the exact large-amplitude pendulum</h2>
          <p>
            Small-angle approximation gives simple harmonic motion; drop it,
            and the pendulum period involves a complete elliptic integral of
            the first kind. The motion itself is sn-function.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="s10" class="scroll-mt-24 pt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">10. Application, KdV cnoidal waves</h2>
          <p>
            The Korteweg–de Vries equation admits travelling-wave solutions
            built from cn², the "cnoidal" waves. Soliton limit recovers sech²
            as the modulus k → 1.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section id="s11" class="scroll-mt-24 pt-8">
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold mb-3">11. Closing the loop</h2>
          <p>
            With the machinery built, re-express the lemniscatic arc length
            from §1 in closed form via the complete elliptic integral. The
            paper ends where it began, with a concrete computation that
            motivated the entire framework.
          </p>
        </section>

        <div class="card mt-10">
          <span class="eyebrow">Full PDF</span>
          <p class="text-ink-800 text-sm">
            The full paper (with all proofs, figures, and worked examples) is
            being typeset in LaTeX with KaTeX-compatible math. It'll be posted
            here once the final pass is done. Reach out on LinkedIn if you'd
            like an advance draft.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="mt-10">
        <a href="/research" class="link-underline text-pow-600 text-sm inline-flex items-center gap-1">
          <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" width="14" height="14" viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round"><line x1="19" y1="12" x2="5" y2="12"></line><polyline points="12 19 5 12 12 5"></polyline></svg>
          Back to all research
        </a>
      </div>
    </article>

    <!-- Sticky TOC -->
    <aside class="hidden lg:block">
      <nav class="sticky top-24 border-l border-ink-800 pl-4 text-sm anim-in anim-stagger-2">
        <p class="eyebrow mb-3">On this page</p>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          {
            toc.map((t) => (
              <li>
                <a
                  href={`#${t.id}`}
                  class="text-ink-800 hover:text-pow-600 transition-colors block leading-snug"
                >
                  {t.label}
                </a>
              </li>
            ))
          }
        </ul>
      </nav>
    </aside>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
